ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach to finding the smallest divisor of n > 1 is straightforward but fundamental. The intuition is simple: since we're looking for the smallest divisor greater than 1, we can systematically test every integer starting from 2 up to n. The first number that divides n evenly (i.e., n % divisor == 0) must be the smallest divisor because we're checking in ascending order. This works because if a number has any divisor other than 1 and itself, the smallest such divisor will be found before larger ones. The algorithm begins by checking if n is less than or equal to 1 (invalid input), then iterates from 2 to n inclusive. For each candidate divisor i, it checks if n % i == 0. If true, it returns i immediately. If the loop completes without finding a divisor (which only happens when n is prime), it returns n itself since prime numbers have no divisors other than 1 and themselves. Time complexity is O(n) in the worst case (when n is prime), and space complexity is O(1) since we only use a few variables. This connects directly to the key subroutine of checking divisibility. Common mistakes include starting the loop from 1 (which would incorrectly return 1), not handling edge cases like n=2 properly, or continuing the loop beyond finding the first divisor. The real pattern is simple iteration with early return.

Pseudocode:
function smallestDivisor(n):
    if n <= 1:
        return -1  # Invalid input
    for i from 2 to n:
        if n % i == 0:
            return i
    return n  # For prime numbers

Time: O(n) worst case, O(√n) average for composite numbers
Space: O(1)

This sub-routine forms the core of the brute force approach. The intuition is that to find the smallest divisor, we need to test numbers in increasing order until we find one that divides n evenly. By starting at 2 and moving upward, we guarantee that the first successful divisor we encounter is indeed the smallest possible divisor greater than 1. This works because divisibility is transitive - if a larger number divides n, all its factors would also divide n, and we would have encountered a smaller factor first if we're checking in ascending order. The algorithm takes an integer n as input and uses a simple for loop from 2 to n. For each iteration, it calculates n % i (remainder when n is divided by i). If the remainder is 0, i divides n evenly and we return i immediately. If the loop completes without finding any divisor, we return n itself (which handles prime numbers). Time complexity is O(n) in worst case when n is prime, but could be much faster for composite numbers. Space complexity is O(1). This connects to the full problem as the main algorithmic component. Common mistakes include: forgetting to handle prime numbers (infinite loop or wrong return), starting loop from 1 instead of 2, or not using early return and continuing to check unnecessary numbers. The pattern is linear search with early termination.

Pseudocode:
function findFirstDivisor(n):
    for i from 2 to n:
        if n % i == 0:
            return i
    return n

Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)

The core insight of the brute force approach is the early return mechanism. Instead of checking all possible divisors and then determining the smallest, we check in ascending order and return immediately upon finding the first divisor. This optimization is crucial because: 1) It ensures we get the smallest divisor (since we're checking from smallest to largest), 2) It saves computation time by avoiding unnecessary checks once we've found our answer, and 3) It simplifies the logic by eliminating the need to track and compare multiple candidates. The intuition is based on the mathematical property that if a number has divisors, the smallest divisor (greater than 1) will be encountered first when checking numbers in increasing order. The algorithm implements this by having a loop that starts at 2 and increments. Inside the loop, we test divisibility using the modulo operator. As soon as we find a number i where n % i == 0, we exit the function and return i. If we complete the loop without finding any divisor, we know n is prime and return n itself. Time complexity benefits significantly from early return - for composite numbers with small divisors, we might exit in O(1) or O(√n) time. Space complexity remains O(1). This connects to the key sub-routine as its optimization strategy. Common mistakes include: continuing the loop after finding a divisor, using a separate variable to track the minimum instead of early return, or incorrectly handling the loop bounds. The pattern is search with short-circuit evaluation.

Pseudocode:
function findSmallestByEarlyReturn(n):
    for i in range(2, n+1):
        if n % i == 0:
            return i  # Early exit
    return n

Time: O(k) where k is smallest divisor, worst case O(n)
Space: O(1)
